You are given a tree with NNN vertices numbered 1,2,вЂ¦,N1, 2, \ldots, N1,2,вЂ¦,N. First, you sort the adjacency lists of all the vertices and run depth first search from node 111. This gives you an array of dfs start times. Note that the start times are uniquely determined, as the adjacency list of each vertex is sorted. The following code represents the dfs:

`    // let st denote the start times
    // let adj[x] be the adjacency list (the list of neighbors) of x
    int timer = 1;
    void dfs(int s, int p){
        st[s] = timer;
        timer++;
        // iterate over the neighbors in increasing order
        sort(adj[s].begin(), adj[s].end());
        for(int v: adj[s]) {
            if(v != p){
                dfs(v, s);
            }
        }
    }
`The timer is initialized with 111 in the beginning, and you call dfs(1,0)(1, 0)(1,0) to compute all the start times. Let stvst_vstvвЂ‹ denote the start time of vvv.

